# Godot GDScript Typing Safety

Use explicit types to avoid parser/type-inference instability in Godot 4.x GDScript.

## Must

- Prefer explicit variable types (`var value: bool = ...`) when the right-hand side may be `Variant` or node-typed.
- Add explicit return types to helper functions whenever possible (`-> bool`, `-> StringName`, etc.).
- Normalize node types before property access when type inference is ambiguous (for example, cache `%HurtBox` as `Area2D`).
- Convert `Dictionary.get()` / metadata / dynamic array values to typed locals before passing them deeper into logic.

## Must not

- Do not use `:=` with node property reads like `%Node.property` unless the node variable is already strongly typed.
- Do not use `:=` directly with `Dictionary.get(...)`, `Object.get(...)`, `get_meta(...)`, or other dynamic-return APIs.
- Do not rely on implicit typing at API boundaries (scene nodes, dictionaries, resources loaded dynamically).

## Allowed shorthand (`:=`) cases

- Numeric/string/vector/color literals and constants with obvious static type.
- Constructors with clear static type (`Vector2.ZERO`, `Color.WHITE`, `CharacterStats.new()`).
- Values returned by functions with explicit return type and stable API contract.

## Review checklist

- Any new `:=` has a statically obvious right-hand-side type.
- Any new scene node property access from `%Node` is typed or cast where needed.
- Any new dictionary/metadata extraction is normalized to typed locals before use.
